    "recap_headline": "Quinnipiac University",
    "recap_text": "Hamden, Conn. \u2013\nThe Quinnipiac Bobcats dropped game one of the series to the Manhattan Jaspers by a final score of 6-5. With the loss, the Bobcats fell to 6-12 on the season and 1-3 in MAAC play.\nSCORE\nManhattan 6, Quinnipiac 5\nRECORDS\nQuinnipiac (6-12, 1-3 MAAC) | Manhattan (7-11, 2-5 MAAC)\nWinning Pitcher \u2013 Jackson Klein (2-0)\nLosing Pitcher \u2013\nMike Poncini\n(0-2)\nHOW IT HAPPENED\nThe Bobcats struck first in this one as\nChristian Smith\ncame home to score on a groundout from\nJack Balcer\n.\nManhattan responded with a couple of runs in the third inning to jump out in front, 2-1. Quinnipiac immediately got the run back in the next half inning as Smith reached on a fielder's choice, allowing\nKyle Garbowski\nto come in and score.\nThe Jaspers would have the answer yet again, scoring the game's next two runs to take a 4-2 lead at the end of five innings.\nQuinnipiac wouldn't go down without a fight as\nJames Marino\nlaunched a three-run homer to put the Bobcats up 5-4 in the top half of the seventh inning.\nOnce again, Manhattan would have the response, going up 6-5 in the bottom half of the seventh and holding on to win the opening game of the series.\nNEWS AND NOTES\nFive different Bobcats recorded hits in the series opener against Manhattan. Three of those Bobcats recorded multiple hits in the effort.\nJames Marino\nled the offense, going 3-for-4 at the plate and driving in three runs. Marino hit his second home run of the season, which now leads the team.\nChristian Smith\nand\nJack Balcer\npicked up two hits and an RBI each.\nBrendan Edvardsen\nand\nCaden Williamson\nwere the other Bobcats to record a hit in the effort.\nJames Pazdera\ngot the start for the Bobcats and went 4.2 innings, allowing two earned runs and striking out one.\nMike Poncini\npitched the next 2.1 innings, striking out three and allowing two runs.\nJ.c. Franconere pitched a scoreless inning in relief, striking out two in the inning.\nON DECK\nThe Bobcats and Jaspers will go back at it tomorrow at 6:30 PM from Clover Stadium in Pomona, New York.",
